Here is a simple Node.js program to print out "Hello World" in the console:

```javascript
// Load the http module to create an http server.
const http = require('http');

// Configure our HTTP server to respond with Hello World to all requests.
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    res.writeHead(200, {"Content-Type": "text/plain"});
    res.end("Hello World\n");
});

// Listen on port 8000, IP defaults to 127.0.0.1
server.listen(8000);

// Put a friendly message on the terminal
console.log("Server running at http://127.0.0.1:8000/");
```

To run this program, save it to a file with a `.js` extension, such as `hello_world.js`. Then, open your command-line interface, navigate to the directory where you saved the file, and run `node hello_world.js`. You should see the message "Server running at http://127.0.0.1:8000/" printed to the console, and if you open a web browser and navigate to `http://127.0.0.1:8000`, you should see the message "Hello World".

